    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 12,
    "last_activity_date" : 1430136649,
    "last_edit_date" : 1430136649,
    "creation_date" : 1408441466,
    "answer_id" : 25380286,
    "question_id" : 7142622,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>@Inject</code> has no 'required' attribute</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5590792,
      "reputation" : 201,
      "user_id" : 4430073,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5e31c9e6d3242f10686178be14440f41?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Keyur Vyas",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4430073/keyur-vyas"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 16,
    "last_activity_date" : 1574171421,
    "last_edit_date" : 1574171421,
    "creation_date" : 1434944390,
    "answer_id" : 30971805,
    "question_id" : 7142622,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In addition to the above:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>The default scope for <code>@Autowired</code> beans is <em>Singleton</em> whereas using JSR 330 <code>@Inject</code> annotation it is like <em>Spring's prototype</em>.</li>\n<li>There is no equivalent of @Lazy in JSR 330 using <code>@Inject</code>.</li>\n<li>There is no equivalent of @Value in JSR 330 using <code>@Inject</code>.</li>\n</ol>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 2812914,
        "reputation" : 1662,
        "user_id" : 2418764,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 50,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b518a39e56c0e62243ec9826dc845655?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Alex Theedom",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2418764/alex-theedom"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1455365350,
      "post_id" : 33015531,
      "comment_id" : 58464169,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "Even though the &#39;@Inject&#39; does not have a required attribute the Java Docs state: Injection of members annotated with &#39;@Inject&#39; is required. Which seems to imply that if an member is not found its inject will fail. See Java Docs: <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javaee/7/api/javax/inject/Inject.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">docs.oracle.com/javaee/7/api/javax/inject/Inject.html</a>"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "user_type" : "does_not_exist",
      "display_name" : "user1134181"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 16,
    "last_activity_date" : 1535293223,
    "last_edit_date" : 1535293223,
    "creation_date" : 1444306543,
    "answer_id" : 33015531,
    "question_id" : 7142622,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>@Autowired</code> annotation is defined in the Spring framework.</p>\n\n<p><code>@Inject</code> annotation is a standard annotation, which is defined in the standard <a href=\"https://jcp.org/en/jsr/detail?id=330\" rel=\"noreferrer\">\"Dependency Injection for Java\" (JSR-330)</a>. Spring (since the version 3.0) supports the generalized model of dependency injection which is defined in the standard JSR-330. (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google_Guice\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Google Guice frameworks</a> and <a href=\"http://picocontainer.com/web\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Picocontainer framework</a> also support this model).</p>\n\n<p>With <code>@Inject</code> can be injected the reference to the implementation of the  <code>Provider</code> interface, which allows injecting the deferred references.</p>\n\n<p>Annotations <code>@Inject</code> and <code>@Autowired</code>- is almost complete analogies. As well as <code>@Autowired</code> annotation, <code>@Inject</code> annotation can be used for automatic binding properties, methods, and constructors.</p>\n\n<p>In contrast to <code>@Autowired</code> annotation, <code>@Inject</code> annotation has no <code>required</code> attribute. Therefore, if the dependencies will not be found - will be thrown an exception.</p>\n\n<p>There are also differences in the clarifications of the binding properties. If there is ambiguity in the choice of components for the injection the <code>@Named</code> qualifier should be added. In a similar situation for <code>@Autowired</code> annotation will be added <code>@Qualifier</code> qualifier (JSR-330 defines it's own <code>@Qualifier</code> annotation and via this qualifier annotation <code>@Named</code> is defined).</p>\n"
  }, {
