      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "On most of projects I saw Autowired rather than Inject. I understand the rationale of the answer but I cannot upvote."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 7839032,
        "reputation" : 101,
        "user_id" : 5925938,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/68000d12a66cddf0b03cf612a3b81b97?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "Adam Bodrogi",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5925938/adam-bodrogi"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1672701933,
      "post_id" : 33944267,
      "comment_id" : 132331353,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "I understand the agnostic approach, but I think at this level it just doesn&#39;t work. If you would like to be agnostic, don&#39;t use any frameworks, because they ultimately define how you write your code and after that if you prefer to change it, you&#39;ll end up with a code future devs will never understand why was it written like that. However on higher levels, like defining the API of your code, I agree with the agnostic approach. &quot;Code for the interface, not for the implementation.&quot;"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 7090908,
      "reputation" : 596,
      "user_id" : 5426099,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d0cb766d56ab9de61b336cf0672126bf?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "tech.yenduri",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5426099/tech-yenduri"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 16,
    "last_activity_date" : 1448558857,
    "creation_date" : 1448558857,
    "answer_id" : 33944267,
    "question_id" : 7142622,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Better use @Inject all the time. Because it is java configuration approach(provided by sun) which makes our application agnostic to the framework. So if you spring also your classes will work.</p>\n\n<p>If you use @Autowired it will works only with spring because @Autowired is spring provided annotation.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 13081809,
      "reputation" : 93,
      "user_id" : 9452134,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/226e9c8545e71d8582c5086ae7547be4?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Kushani5j",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/9452134/kushani5j"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1523443651,
    "last_edit_date" : 1523443651,
    "creation_date" : 1523440795,
    "answer_id" : 49772089,
    "question_id" : 7142622,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>The <code>@Inject</code> annotation is one of the JSR-330 annotations collection. This has Match by Type,Match by Qualifier, Match by Name execution paths.\nThese execution paths are valid for both setter and field injection.The behavior of <code>@Autowired</code> annotation is same as the <code>@Inject</code> annotation. The only difference is the <code>@Autowired</code> annotation is a part of the Spring framework. <code>@Autowired</code> annotation also has the above execution paths. So I recommend the <code>@Autowired</code> for your answer.</p>\n"
  }, {
