    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 7117652,
      "reputation" : 2418,
      "user_id" : 5443319,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 0,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0b9473fc90769616670bc034a135fd5f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Ziaullhaq Savanur",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5443319/ziaullhaq-savanur"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1592468120,
    "creation_date" : 1592468120,
    "answer_id" : 62445419,
    "question_id" : 7142622,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>@Autowired(required=false)\nBy default the dependency injection for @Autowired must be fulfilled because the value of required attribute is true by default. We can change this behavior by using @Autowired(required=false). In this case if bean is not found for dependency injection, it will not through error.</p>\n\n<p>Please have look at \n<a href=\"https://www.concretepage.com/spring/spring-autowired-annotation#required-false\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://www.concretepage.com/spring/spring-autowired-annotation#required-false</a></p>\n\n<p>But @Inject doesn’t need (required=false) it will not through error if dependency is not found</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4554063,
      "reputation" : 1747,
      "user_id" : 8450064,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/8Prnv.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Anil Nivargi",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/8450064/anil-nivargi"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1713102455,
    "creation_date" : 1713102455,
    "answer_id" : 78323991,
    "question_id" : 7142622,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Inject and Autowired both serves the same functionality i.e to inject the bean.</p>\n<p><strong>@Inject</strong> - It's defined in the javax.inject package and it's part of Java.<br />\nIf your application is not spring framework then use Inject annotation as it's part of java.</p>\n<p><strong>@Autowired</strong> – It's defined in the package org.springframework.bean.factory and part of Spring framework.\nIf your application is Spring based application then better use Autowired annotation.</p>\n"
  } ],
